t 29.42pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">  Competent persons schemes</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36.9pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Personal Details</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My name is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Harold </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Roger Lovegrove.  I am an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Inc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">orporated Electrical Engineer, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Fellow of the Institution of Engineering Technology.  I have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">been </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in the electrical installation industry all of my working life: apprentice, electrician, contracts engineer, manager, managing director.   Consultant for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">25 years  specialis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in Inspection and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">esting </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lectrical </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nstallations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">investigating electrical installation problems </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">roviding electrical installation condition reports</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Also I provide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">expert witness </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">services and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reports.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reasons for support</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I strongly support the need of a single electrical safety register as launched by the ECA and the ESC for electrical contractors operating in the domestic and commercial / industrial electrical installation market place for the following reasons:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The regi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ster will be of great </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">benefit to consumers, clients and specifiers as a single </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reference </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">point to  source a competent electrical contractor.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I have found many installations that are sub-standard and many with dangerous conditions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Invariably the cause ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s been incompetence of the installer: poor workmanship; a lack of technical knowledge; non-compliance with Wiring Regulations, BS 7671.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Building Regulations Part P</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Previous governments set up Part P of the Building regulations with the intention of improv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing the saf</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ety of electrical installations in dwellings.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Part P made it a legal requirement for electrical installation work in dwellings to comply with the BS7671</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Requirements for Electrical Installations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The IE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Wiring Regulations.  Most competent el</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ectrical contractors understand these regulations and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Part P </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">requirement to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be registered with a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">competence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">persons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> scheme provider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Hence in the main Part P </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was welcomed by electrical contractors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The requirements of Part P were originally fairly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">estrictive for non-electrical persons and DIY installers to undertake electrical installation work.  In my view Part P has been very effective. It has improved competence in the industry and made DIYer’s more aware of the dangers electricity can create in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">their homes.  The downside that Building </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Control </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Departments have been unable to adequately police the system.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 2011 revision to Part P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has watered down the technical requirements of Part P, also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">now permits electrical installation work to be carrie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d out by unqualified persons providing the work is checked and certified by a competent third party.  This part of the revision is not yet in operation as there are no third party competent person schemes yet in operation. Until </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">there is, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">home safety standards </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are likely  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to drop back to pre-2005 standards</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the door is open again for Rogue traders and DYEers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Competent Persons Scheme Operators.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">At the onset of Part P there wer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">six or seven s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cheme operators. Some of which have been in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">place for many years enabling contractors to register voluntarily.  Some schemes typically NICEIC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> well known in the construction </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">industry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> also to Local Authorities and Housing Associations etc.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Because there are so many different </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">scheme </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">operators each</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> having their own rules and criteria, standards and qualifying requirements are wide and varied.  Some of the operators provide training courses to their own standards and specifications</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">here is no common denominator.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Also t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">here needs to be a common appr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oach to training </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not only to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">contractors </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">trainers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who train them.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Most scheme operators are monitored by UKAS but this does not necessarily mean that there is a common standard or common procedures in place.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Competition between </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">scheme </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">operators means that standards vary.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I understand that s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ome operators </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> only carry out a ‘desk top’ assessment of an applicant whereas others will insist on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">always </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">visiting the contracto</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s premises, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">examin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the business</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> procedures</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, documentation a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nd equipment,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prior to inspecting some of the contractor’s on-site installation work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Discipline is another issue.  It is not uncommon for a contractor who has been removed from a register for bad work or other serious non-conformity to become registered </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with another scheme operator almost immediately without any reference being made to the original operator’s reasons for removal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I have seen a contractor advertising registration </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with two scheme operators. When questioned I was informed that he was given </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">registration by the second operator in order to promote their scheme. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">From the foregoing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> it can be seen that the present situation with a number of scheme operators having various standards is most unsatisfactory from not only a safety perspective but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">also for public perception of the effectiveness of the Part P legislation.  I therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">submit that it is of paramount importance </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">for there to be a single </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">not for profit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> scheme provider monitored by UKAS rather than a number of operators working to their own agenda and possible profitability.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">30 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>